{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01B6FZKLAu1JUMysGDQHTegY","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Cloche Usage\n     2→\n     3→Cloche runs containerized workflows for autonomous coding agents. You define a\n     4→workflow graph in the `.cloche` DSL, Cloche copies your project into a Docker\n     5→container, runs the workflow steps (agent prompts and shell scripts), and extracts\n     6→results to a git branch.\n     7→\n     8→## Core Concepts\n     9→\n    10→- **Workflow**: A directed graph of steps connected by named-result wiring.\n    11→- **Step**: A unit of work. Type is inferred: `prompt` = agent step, `run` = script step, `workflow_name` = workflow step (host only).\n    12→- **Result**: A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. `success`, `fail`, `needs-research`). Steps declare their possible results; the engine follows wiring based on the reported result.\n    13→- **Wiring**: Maps `step:result` pairs to the next step. Separate from step definitions.\n    14→- **Terminals**: `done` (success) and `abort` (failure) are built-in terminal targets.\n    15→\n    16→## Workflow DSL\n    17→\n    18→Workflow files use the `.cloche` extension and live in `.cloche/`. The first step\n    19→declared is the entry point. Graphs are validated at parse time (all results wired,\n    20→no orphans, entry point exists).\n    21→\n    22→### Minimal Example\n    23→\n    24→```\n    25→workflow \"develop\" {\n    26→  step implement {\n    27→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    28→    results = [success, fail]\n    29→  }\n    30→\n    31→  step test {\n    32→    run = \"make test 2>&1\"\n    33→    results = [success, fail]\n    34→  }\n    35→\n    36→  implement:success -> test\n    37→  implement:fail -> abort\n    38→  test:success -> done\n    39→  test:fail -> abort\n    40→}\n    41→```\n    42→\n    43→### Step Configuration\n    44→\n    45→| Key | Type | Description |\n    46→|-----|------|-------------|\n    47→| `prompt` | string or `file(\"path\")` | Prompt template. Makes this an agent step. |\n    48→| `run` | string | Shell command. Makes this a script step. |\n    49→| `workflow_name` | string | Container workflow to dispatch. Makes this a workflow step (host only). |\n    50→| `results` | ident list | Declared result names, e.g. `[success, fail, give-up]`. |\n    51→| `max_attempts` | string | Max retries before automatic `give-up` result, e.g. `\"2\"`. |\n    52→| `timeout` | string | Step timeout as Go duration, e.g. `\"30m\"`, `\"2h\"`. Default: 30m. |\n    53→| `agent_command` | string | Agent binary name(s), comma-separated for fallback chains, e.g. `\"claude,gemini\"`. |\n    54→| `agent_args` | string | Override default agent arguments. |\n    55→| `feedback` | string | Set to `\"true\"` to include `.cloche/output/*.log` content in the prompt. |\n    56→| `prompt_step` | string | For workflow steps: which preceding step's output to use as the prompt. |\n    57→\n    58→A step must have exactly one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`.\n    59→\n    60→### The `file()` Function\n    61→\n    62→`file(\"path\")` reads the file at the given path relative to the working directory\n    63→(`/workspace/` in containers) at execution time, not parse time. Use it for prompt\n    64→templates:\n    65→\n    66→```\n    67→prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    68→```\n    69→\n    70→### The `container {}` Block\n    71→\n    72→Can appear at step level or workflow level. Keys are stored with a `container.` prefix.\n    73→\n    74→**Step level** — per-step container config:\n    75→```\n    76→step code {\n    77→  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    78→  container {\n    79→    image         = \"custom-agent:v2\"\n    80→    memory        = \"4g\"\n    81→    network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\", \"api.example.com\"]\n    82→  }\n    83→  results = [success, fail]\n    84→}\n    85→```\n    86→\n    87→**Workflow level** — defaults for all steps:\n    88→```\n    89→workflow \"develop\" {\n    90→  container {\n    91→    agent_command = \"gemini\"\n    92→    image         = \"myregistry/myimage:v2\"\n    93→    memory        = \"4g\"\n    94→  }\n    95→  ...\n    96→}\n    97→```\n    98→\n    99→Supported keys: `image`, `memory`, `network_allow`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n   100→\n   101→### Wiring Syntax\n   102→\n   103→Connect steps with `step:result -> next_step`:\n   104→\n   105→```\n   106→implement:success -> test\n   107→implement:fail -> abort\n   108→test:success -> done\n   109→test:fail -> fix\n   110→```\n   111→\n   112→### Wire Output Mappings\n   113→\n   114→Extract values from a step's JSON output and inject as env vars into the target:\n   115→\n   116→```\n   117→step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   118→```\n   119→\n   120→Path expressions:\n   121→\n   122→| Expression | Meaning |\n   123→|---|---|\n   124→| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   125→| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   126→| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   127→| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   128→| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   129→\n   130→If the output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the structure. If it's plain\n   131→text, only bare `output` works.\n   132→\n   133→### Retry Loops\n   134→\n   135→Wire failures back to earlier steps:\n   136→\n   137→```\n   138→test:fail -> fix\n   139→fix:success -> test    // retry the test\n   140→fix:fail -> abort\n   141→```\n   142→\n   143→Use `max_attempts` to cap retries. When exhausted, the step returns `give-up`:\n   144→\n   145→```\n   146→step fix {\n   147→  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n   148→  max_attempts = \"2\"\n   149→  results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   150→}\n   151→```\n   152→\n   153→### Parallel Branches (Fanout)\n   154→\n   155→Wire one result to multiple targets for concurrent execution:\n   156→\n   157→```\n   158→test:success -> lint\n   159→test:success -> quality\n   160→```\n   161→\n   162→### Collect (Join)\n   163→\n   164→Synchronize parallel branches:\n   165→\n   166→```\n   167→collect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   168→collect any(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   169→```\n   170→\n   171→`all` fires when every condition is met. `any` fires when at least one is.\n   172→\n   173→### Comments\n   174→\n   175→Line comments with `//`:\n   176→\n   177→```\n   178→// This is a comment\n   179→implement:success -> test  // inline comment\n   180→```\n   181→\n   182→## Result Protocol\n   183→\n   184→Steps report results by printing a marker line to stdout:\n   185→\n   186→```\n   187→CLOCHE_RESULT:<name>\n   188→```\n   189→\n   190→For example: `CLOCHE_RESULT:success`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:needs-research`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:give-up`.\n   191→\n   192→Rules:\n   193→- The **last** `CLOCHE_RESULT:` line wins if multiple are printed.\n   194→- Marker lines are **stripped** from captured output (not passed to logs or downstream steps).\n   195→- The result name must match one of the step's declared `results`.\n   196→- For script steps with no marker: exit 0 = `success`, exit non-zero = `fail`.\n   197→- For agent steps: if exit non-zero with a marker, the marker result is used. If exit non-zero without a marker, falls back to the next agent in the fallback chain (or returns `fail` if last).\n   198→\n   199→## Prompt Assembly\n   200→\n   201→When an agent step runs, Cloche assembles a prompt from these sections (joined by blank lines):\n   202→\n   203→1. **Step template**: The step's `prompt` content (inline string or resolved `file(\"path\")`).\n   204→2. **User request**: Content of `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt` (set via `--prompt` flag), prefixed with `## User Request`.\n   205→3. **Validation output** (opt-in): If `feedback = \"true\"`, reads all `.log` files from `.cloche/output/` and includes them prefixed with `## Validation Output`.\n   206→4. **Result selection**: Lists the step's declared results with instructions to print exactly one `CLOCHE_RESULT:<name>` marker.\n   207→\n   208→The assembled prompt is passed to the agent command via stdin.\n   209→\n   210→## Agent Command Resolution\n   211→\n   212→Priority (highest to lowest):\n   213→1. Step-level `agent_command`\n   214→2. Workflow-level `container { agent_command }`\n   215→3. `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` environment variable\n   216→4. Default: `claude`\n   217→\n   218→### Fallback Chains\n   219→\n   220→Comma-separated commands are tried in order:\n   221→\n   222→```\n   223→agent_command = \"claude,gemini,codex\"\n   224→```\n   225→\n   226→- **Command not found / failed to start** — try next command\n   227→- **Exit non-zero without `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — try next command\n   228→- **Exit non-zero with `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — use that result (no fallback)\n   229→- **Exit 0** — use result (no fallback)\n   230→- **All commands fail to start** — step returns an error\n   231→- **Last command crashes without marker** — step returns `fail`\n   232→\n   233→Known agents (e.g. `claude`) get default arguments (`-p --output-format stream-json --verbose --dangerously-skip-permissions`). Unknown agents receive the prompt on stdin with no flags. Override with `agent_args`.\n   234→\n   235→## Workflow Locations\n   236→\n   237→**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) run inside Docker\n   238→via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type.\n   239→\n   240→**Host workflow** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) runs on the host machine as the daemon.\n   241→Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow_name` step type\n   242→dispatches a container workflow run and blocks until it completes.\n   243→\n   244→### Host Workflow Example\n   245→\n   246→```\n   247→workflow \"main\" {\n   248→  step ready-tasks {\n   249→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh 1\"\n   250→    results = [success, fail]\n   251→  }\n   252→\n   253→  step prepare-prompt {\n   254→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   255→    results = [success, fail]\n   256→  }\n   257→\n   258→  step develop {\n   259→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   260→    results       = [success, fail]\n   261→  }\n   262→\n   263→  ready-tasks:success -> prepare-prompt [\n   264→    CLOCHE_TASK_ID    = output[0].id,\n   265→    CLOCHE_TASK_TITLE = output[0].title,\n   266→    CLOCHE_TASK_BODY  = output[0].description\n   267→  ]\n   268→  ready-tasks:fail       -> abort\n   269→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop [ CLOCHE_TASK_ID = output.task_id ]\n   270→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   271→  develop:success        -> done\n   272→  develop:fail           -> done\n   273→}\n   274→```\n   275→\n   276→### Host Step Environment Variables\n   277→\n   278→| Variable | Description |\n   279→|----------|-------------|\n   280→| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Absolute path to the project directory on the host. |\n   281→| `CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT` | Path where this step should write its output (for output mappings). |\n   282→| `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT` | Path to the output file from the immediately preceding step. |\n   283→| Wire-mapped vars | Any env vars declared in wire output mappings (e.g. `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`). |\n   284→\n   285→### Container Environment Variables\n   286→\n   287→| Variable | Description |\n   288→|----------|-------------|\n   289→| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n   290→| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | Passed through from the host if set. |\n   291→| `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` | Overrides the default agent command inside the container. |\n   292→\n   293→## Complete Example: Container Workflow with Parallel Validation\n   294→\n   295→```\n   296→workflow \"develop\" {\n   297→  step implement {\n   298→    prompt = file(\"prompts/implement.md\")\n   299→    results = [success, fail]\n   300→  }\n   301→\n   302→  step test {\n   303→    run = \"bundle exec rake test 2>&1\"\n   304→    results = [success, fail]\n   305→  }\n   306→\n   307→  step lint {\n   308→    run = \"bundle exec rubocop 2>&1\"\n   309→    results = [success, fail]\n   310→  }\n   311→\n   312→  step quality {\n   313→    run = \"python3 scripts/quality-check.py 2>&1\"\n   314→    results = [success, fail]\n   315→  }\n   316→\n   317→  step fix {\n   318→    prompt = file(\"prompts/fix.md\")\n   319→    max_attempts = \"2\"\n   320→    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   321→  }\n   322→\n   323→  implement:success -> test\n   324→  implement:fail -> abort\n   325→\n   326→  test:success -> lint\n   327→  test:success -> quality\n   328→  test:fail -> fix\n   329→\n   330→  lint:fail -> fix\n   331→  quality:fail -> fix\n   332→  collect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   333→\n   334→  fix:success -> test\n   335→  fix:fail -> abort\n   336→  fix:give-up -> abort\n   337→}\n   338→```\n   339→\n   340→## Container Isolation Model\n   341→\n   342→- **Files in**: `docker cp` copies the project into `/workspace/`. No bind mounts. Override files from `.cloche/overrides/` are applied on top. `.git/` is included.\n   343→- **Files out**: On completion, the daemon extracts results via `docker cp` into a git worktree and commits to a `cloche/<run-id>` branch.\n   344→- **Auth mounts**: `~/.claude` and `~/.claude.json` are bind-mounted read-only for Claude Code session reuse.\n   345→- **Network**: Containers have network access (needed for API calls).\n   346→- **Cleanup**: Containers are removed after successful runs unless `--keep-container` is set. Failed runs always keep their container.\n   347→\n   348→Your project directory is never modified by the container.\n   349→\n   350→## CLI Reference\n   351→\n   352→### `cloche init`\n   353→\n   354→Scaffold a new Cloche project.\n   355→\n   356→```\n   357→cloche init [--workflow <name>] [--base-image <base>]\n   358→```\n   359→\n   360→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   361→|------|---------|-------------|\n   362→| `--workflow <name>` | `develop` | Workflow name. Creates `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n   363→| `--base-image <base>` | `cloche-base:latest` | Base Docker image for the generated Dockerfile. |\n   364→\n   365→Creates `.cloche/` with workflow file, Dockerfile, `config.toml`, prompt templates,\n   366→host workflow (`host.cloche`), and prompt generation script. Skips existing files.\n   367→\n   368→### `cloche run`\n   369→\n   370→Launch a workflow run.\n   371→\n   372→```\n   373→cloche run --workflow <name> [--prompt \"...\"] [--title \"...\"] [--keep-container]\n   374→```\n   375→\n   376→| Flag | Description |\n   377→|------|-------------|\n   378→| `--workflow <name>` | Workflow name. Resolves to `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n   379→| `--prompt \"...\"`, `-p` | Inline prompt written to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt`. |\n   380→| `--title \"...\"` | One-line summary for status display. Auto-generated if omitted. |\n   381→| `--keep-container` | Keep container on success (failed runs always keep it). |\n   382→\n   383→Must be run from inside a git repository. The daemon auto-rebuilds the Docker image\n   384→when `.cloche/Dockerfile` changes.\n   385→\n   386→### `cloche status`\n   387→\n   388→```\n   389→cloche status <run-id>\n   390→```\n   391→\n   392→Shows run title, type (`host`/`container`), state, active steps, and per-step results.\n   393→\n   394→### `cloche list`\n   395→\n   396→```\n   397→cloche list [--all]\n   398→```\n   399→\n   400→Lists runs from the last hour (or all with `--all`).\n   401→\n   402→### `cloche logs`\n   403→\n   404→```\n   405→cloche logs <run-id> [--step <name>] [--type <full|script|llm>] [--follow]\n   406→```\n   407→\n   408→| Flag | Description |\n   409→|------|-------------|\n   410→| `--step <name>` | Show only logs for the specified step. |\n   411→| `--type <full\\|script\\|llm>` | Log type filter. |\n   412→| `--follow`, `-f` | Stream live logs via SSE (requires `CLOCHE_HTTP`). |\n   413→\n   414→### `cloche poll`\n   415→\n   416→```\n   417→cloche poll <run-id>\n   418→```\n   419→\n   420→Block until the run finishes. Polls every 2 seconds. Exits 0 on success, 1 on failure.\n   421→\n   422→### `cloche stop`\n   423→\n   424→```\n   425→cloche stop <run-id>\n   426→```\n   427→\n   428→### `cloche delete`\n   429→\n   430→```\n   431→cloche delete <container-or-run-id>\n   432→```\n   433→\n   434→Delete a retained Docker container by container ID or run ID.\n   435→\n   436→### `cloche health`\n   437→\n   438→```\n   439→cloche health\n   440→```\n   441→\n   442→Show per-project pass/fail summary. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP`.\n   443→\n   444→### `cloche shutdown`\n   445→\n   446→```\n   447→cloche shutdown\n   448→```\n   449→\n   450→## Project Layout\n   451→\n   452→```\n   453→my-project/\n   454→├── .cloche/\n   455→│   ├── develop.cloche        # Container workflow\n   456→│   ├── host.cloche           # Host orchestration workflow\n   457→│   ├── Dockerfile            # Container image definition\n   458→│   ├── config.toml           # Project configuration\n   459→│   ├── prompts/              # Prompt templates\n   460→│   │   ├── implement.md\n   461→│   │   ├── fix.md\n   462→│   │   └── update-docs.md\n   463→│   ├── scripts/              # Host-side scripts\n   464→│   ├── overrides/            # Files copied on top of /workspace/\n   465→│   │   └── CLAUDE.md         # Container-specific CLAUDE.md (optional)\n   466→│   └── <run-id>/             # Runtime state (gitignored)\n   467→│       ├── prompt.txt        # User prompt\n   468→│       ├── output/\n   469→│       │   ├── full.log      # Unified log\n   470→│       │   ├── test.log      # Per-step script output\n   471→│       │   └── llm-impl.log  # Per-step LLM conversation\n   472→│       ├── attempt_count/    # Retry counters for max_attempts\n   473→│       └── history.log       # Step execution log\n   474→├── src/                      # Project source (untouched by Cloche)\n   475→└── .git/\n   476→```\n   477→\n   478→## Daemon Configuration\n   479→\n   480→| Variable | Default | Description |\n   481→|----------|---------|-------------|\n   482→| `CLOCHE_LISTEN` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Listen address |\n   483→| `CLOCHE_DB` | `cloche.db` | SQLite database path |\n   484→| `CLOCHE_RUNTIME` | `docker` | `docker` or `local` (subprocess, for dev only) |\n   485→| `CLOCHE_IMAGE` | `cloche-agent:latest` | Default Docker image |\n   486→| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | _(unset)_ | HTTP address for web dashboard. Not started unless set. |\n   487→| `CLOCHE_AGENT_PATH` | _(auto)_ | Path to `cloche-agent` binary (local runtime) |\n   488→| `CLOCHE_LLM_COMMAND` | _(unset)_ | Command for LLM calls (evolution, merge conflicts) |\n   489→| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | _(unset)_ | Passed into Docker containers |\n   490→| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS` | _(unset)_ | Extra bind mounts (comma-separated `host:container`) |\n   491→| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` | _(unset)_ | Extra env vars (comma-separated `KEY=VALUE`) |\n   492→\n   493→### Client Configuration\n   494→\n   495→| Variable | Default | Description |\n   496→|----------|---------|-------------|\n   497→| `CLOCHE_ADDR` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Daemon gRPC address |\n   498→| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | `localhost:8080` | Daemon HTTP address |\n   499→\n   500→## Dockerfile Requirements\n   501→\n   502→The container image must have:\n   503→- `cloche-agent` binary at `/usr/local/bin/cloche-agent`\n   504→- `git` installed\n   505→- An `agent` user (cloche wraps commands with `chown` + `su agent`)\n   506→- `/workspace` as the working directory\n   507→- Your project's build dependencies and the agent binary (e.g. `claude`)\n   508→\n   509→## Build Commands\n   510→\n   511→```\n   512→make build          # Build all binaries to bin/\n   513→make test           # Run all tests\n   514→make test-short     # Run tests (skip slow ones)\n   515→make lint           # Run go vet\n   516→make proto          # Regenerate gRPC code from protobuf\n   517→make docker-build   # Build the cloche-agent Docker image\n   518→make install        # Build, install to ~/.local/bin/, restart daemon\n   519→make clean          # Remove bin/\n   520→```\n   521→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01FS5WAKvZ54ncrYpdy2SFQf","session_id":"7e3762fb-e565-4c0e-b9b1-9371ff7bfffd","uuid":"5b45d46b-e519-4511-8cc8-65ce0bcb2d75"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TuVK5vJe41ntaYk8kT9AgB","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Workflows\n     2→\n     3→Cloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n     4→\n     5→## Workflow Locations\n     6→\n     7→Cloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n     8→\n     9→**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) — Run inside a Docker\n    10→container via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\n    11→standard workflows for coding tasks.\n    12→\n    13→**Host workflow** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) — Runs on the host machine as the daemon\n    14→process. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\n    15→dispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\n    16→point for custom orchestration strategies.\n    17→\n    18→The convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\n    19→file is a parse error.\n    20→\n    21→## Concepts\n    22→\n    23→| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    24→|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    25→| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    26→| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n    27→| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    28→| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n    29→| done     | Built-in terminal step — successful completion                     |\n    30→| abort    | Built-in terminal step — failure with error reporting              |\n    31→\n    32→## Step Types\n    33→\n    34→Step type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n    35→\n    36→**agent** (has `prompt`) — Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\n    37→to the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\n    38→container. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    39→\n    40→**script** (has `run`) — Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\n    41→any deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    42→\n    43→**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) — Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\n    44→until it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n    45→\n    46→A step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\n    47→parse error.\n    48→\n    49→## DSL Syntax\n    50→\n    51→```\n    52→workflow \"implement-feature\" {\n    53→  step code {\n    54→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    55→    container {\n    56→      image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n    57→      network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\"]\n    58→    }\n    59→    results = [success, fail, retry_with_feedback]\n    60→  }\n    61→\n    62→  step check {\n    63→    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    64→    results = [pass, fail]\n    65→  }\n    66→\n    67→  step review {\n    68→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/review.md\")\n    69→    input = step.code.output\n    70→    results = [approved, changes_requested]\n    71→  }\n    72→\n    73→  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n    74→  code:success -> check\n    75→  code:fail -> abort\n    76→  code:retry_with_feedback -> code\n    77→\n    78→  check:pass -> review\n    79→  check:fail -> code:retry_with_feedback\n    80→\n    81→  review:approved -> done\n    82→  review:changes_requested -> code\n    83→}\n    84→```\n    85→\n    86→## Key Properties\n    87→\n    88→**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\n    89→field makes it a script step.\n    90→\n    91→**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\n    92→report. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n    93→\n    94→**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\n    95→existing ones by rewiring — without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\n    96→Cloche's self-evolution feature.\n    97→\n    98→**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\n    99→wired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n   100→\n   101→## Wire Output Mappings\n   102→\n   103→Wires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\n   104→them as environment variables into the target step:\n   105→\n   106→```\n   107→step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   108→```\n   109→\n   110→The general form:\n   111→\n   112→```\n   113→FROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n   114→```\n   115→\n   116→Where `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\n   117→starting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n   118→\n   119→| Expression | Meaning |\n   120→|---|---|\n   121→| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   122→| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   123→| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   124→| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   125→| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   126→\n   127→If the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\n   128→structure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\n   129→value is converted to a string for env var injection.\n   130→\n   131→If two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\n   132→returns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\n   133→wires to different steps without conflict.\n   134→\n   135→## Host Workflow Example\n   136→\n   137→```\n   138→# .cloche/host.cloche — runs on the host machine\n   139→workflow \"main\" {\n   140→  step ready-tasks {\n   141→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh 1\"\n   142→    results = [success, fail]\n   143→  }\n   144→\n   145→  step prepare-prompt {\n   146→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   147→    results = [success, fail]\n   148→  }\n   149→\n   150→  step develop {\n   151→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   152→    results       = [success, fail]\n   153→  }\n   154→\n   155→  ready-tasks:success -> prepare-prompt [\n   156→    CLOCHE_TASK_ID    = output[0].id,\n   157→    CLOCHE_TASK_TITLE = output[0].title,\n   158→    CLOCHE_TASK_BODY  = output[0].description\n   159→  ]\n   160→  ready-tasks:fail       -> abort\n   161→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop [\n   162→    CLOCHE_TASK_ID = output.task_id\n   163→  ]\n   164→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   165→  develop:success        -> done\n   166→  develop:fail           -> done\n   167→}\n   168→```\n   169→\n   170→The `ready-tasks` step outputs JSON; wire output mappings extract fields and inject\n   171→them as environment variables into `prepare-prompt`. The `workflow_name` step\n   172→dispatches a container workflow run and blocks until it completes.\n   173→\n   174→## Execution Model\n   175→\n   176→**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\n   177→container. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\n   178→wiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\n   179→All steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n   180→\n   181→**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. Script\n   182→steps run via `sh -c`, and workflow steps dispatch container runs via the daemon's\n   183→standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`,\n   184→etc.) are injected into each step.\n   185→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01FS5WAKvZ54ncrYpdy2SFQf","session_id":"7e3762fb-e565-4c0e-b9b1-9371ff7bfffd","uuid":"ac3b7308-9b82-495a-a127-dcb855e58d9d"}
